ctants\n   - Relationship between catalysts and reaction mechanisms\n   - Relationship between intermediate products and final products\n   - Relationship between purification methods and products\n   - Relationship between characterization techniques and product properties\n   - Relationship between crystallization methods and product morphology\n   - Relationship between reaction vessels and reaction conditions\n   - Relationship between safety measures and specific steps\n   - Relationship between storage conditions and product stability\n   - Relationship between reaction atmosphere and reaction mechanism\n   - Relationship between stirring/mixing methods and reaction homogeneity\n   - Relationship between cooling/heating methods and reaction kinetics\n   - Relationship between morphology control factors and product properties\n3. For each identified relationship, extract the following information:\n   - Source entity: The starting entity of the relationship\n   - Target entity: The ending entity of the relationship\n   - Relationship description: Brief explanation of the relationship between the two entities\n   - Relationship strength: A numeric score from 1-5 indicating the importance or closeness of the relationship\n4. Use the following format to output each relationship:\n   (\"relationship\"<|><source_entity><|><target_entity><|><relationship_description><|><relationship_strength>)\n\n## Output Format\n- Use **##** as the delimiter for the list of entities and relationships.\n- All output should be in English.\n- When finished, output <|COMPLETE|>.\n\n## Example 1\nInput text:\nIn a typical nanomaterial synthesis process, 5 millimoles of chloroauric acid (HAuCl4) are dissolved in 20 mL of deionized water. Under continuous stirring, 10 mL of 0.1M sodium citrate solution is slowly added as a reducing agent. The mixture is refluxed at 90°C for 1 hour, during which the solution gradually turns wine-red. The resulting gold nanoparticles are characterized using Transmission Electron Microscopy (TEM). Finally, the nanoparticles are separated by centrifugation and stored at 4°C for future use.\n\nOutput:\n(\"entity\"<|>Chloroauric acid<|>Precursor<|>Gold source for gold nanoparticle synthesis, chemical formula HAuCl4)\n##\n(\"entity\"<|>Deionized water<|>Solvent<|>Pure water used to dissolve reactants)\n##\n(\"entity\"<|>Sodium citrate<|>Reducing agent<|>Compound used to reduce gold ions to form nanoparticles)\n##\n(\"entity\"<|>Gold nanoparticles<|>Product<|>Final target product of the synthesis process)\n##\n(\"entity\"<|>5 millimoles<|>Dosage<|>Amount of chloroauric acid used)\n##\n(\"entity\"<|>20 mL<|>Dosage<|>Amount of deionized water used)\n##\n(\"entity\"<|>10 mL<|>Dosage<|>Amount of sodium citrate solution used)\n##\n(\"entity\"<|>0.1M<|>Concentration<|>Concentration of sodium citrate solution)\n##\n(\"entity\"<|>90°C<|>Reaction condition<|>Temperature of the reflux reaction)\n##\n(\"entity\"<|>1 hour<|>Reaction condition<|>Duration of the reflux reaction)\n##\n(\"entity\"<|>Transmission Electron Microscopy<|>Characterization technique<|>Instrument used to observe the morphology of gold nanoparticles, abbreviated as TEM)\n##\n(\"entity\"<|>Centrifugation<|>Purification method<|>Method used to separate nanoparticles)\n##\n(\"entity\"<|>4°C<|>Storage condition<|>Storage temperature for gold nanoparticles)\n##\n(\"relationship\"<|>Chloroauric acid<|>5 millimoles<|>The dosage of chloroauric acid used is 5 millimoles<|>4)\n##\n(\"relationship\"<|>Deionized water<|>20 mL<|>The amount of deionized water used is 20 mL<|>4)\n##\n(\"relationship\"<|>Sodium citrate<|>Gold nanoparticles<|>Sodium citrate acts as a reducing agent to form gold nanoparticles<|>5)\n##\n(\"relationship\"<|>90°C<|>Gold nanoparticles<|>90°C is the reaction temperature for forming gold nanoparticles<|>4)\n##\n(\"relationship\"<|>Transmission Electron Microscopy<|>Gold nanoparticles<|>Transmission Electron Microscopy is used to characterize the morpholo