 /PMMA/pentacene film.  The longer lifetime of the   $\\mathrm{Cs}\\mathrm{Pb}\\mathrm{Br}_{3}/\\mathrm{PMM}$   is consistent with its stronger fluorescence  intensity. The fast exciton separation at the interface between   $\\mathrm{Cs}\\mathrm{Pb}\\mathrm{Br}_{3}/\\mathrm{PMM}$   hybrid film and pentacene matrix is related  to the shorter lifetime of excitons at the interface between   $\\mathrm{Cs}\\mathrm{Pb}\\mathrm{Br}_{3}/\\mathrm{PMM}$   and pentacene.  \n\nThe output curves of the field effect transistor (FET) based  flash memory measured under the dark condition and with  light illumination are illustrated in  Figure   2 a.  Both the gate  voltage and the incident light can be utilized to modulate the  transport of charge carriers in the semiconducting channel.  The linear and saturation regions clearly prove the typical  p-type behavior of the transistor. The output curves appear linearly under the low bias as shown in Figure S1 (Supporting  Information), which indicates good ohmic contact between the  pentacene and the Au source–drain electrodes.  The extracted  field-effect mobility and on/off ratio of the device in the dark  condition are calculated to be   $0.24~\\mathrm{cm}^{2}\\;\\mathrm{V}^{-1}\\;\\mathrm{s}^{-1}$   and  ${\\approx}1.86\\times10^{5}$  ,  implying the satisfied crystalline quality of the thermally evaporated pentacene film. Compared with the   $I_{\\mathrm{DS}}$   measured in the  dark,   $I_{\\mathrm{DS}}$   achieved under light illumination shows an abrupt  increment.  The influences of the light intensities are further  studied as shown in Figure S2 (Supporting Information), in  which more noticeable enhancement of the current can be  observed with stronger light stimulation.  Figure 2b displays  the photo programmable and electrical-erasable characteristics  of   $\\mathrm{Cs}\\mathrm{Pb}{\\mathrm{Br}}_{3}$   QDs-based flash memory device. Light pulse with a  wavelength of   $365~\\mathrm{nm}$  , intensity of   $0.153\\mathrm{~m